{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:57:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1357"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1357"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.01,0.82,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115676"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1843"},{"type":"tags","id":"1989"},{"type":"tags","id":"1993"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44048"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49329"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115676"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-month-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. His parent reports that he runs around at home for a minute or so at a time before becoming short of breath. He is meeting all developmental milestones. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Cardiovascular examination reveals a widely split S2 heart sound and a thrill felt at the left upper sternal border. The jugular venous pressure is normal, as is the right ventricular impulse. Abdominal examination reveals mild hepatomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Cardiac catheterisation","Exercise tolerance test","Doppler echocardiography","Electrocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical presentation, this child likely has an atrial septal defect (ASD). The most appropriate diagnostic investigation is \u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler echocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E. This non-invasive imaging technique uses high-frequency sound waves to create detailed images of the heart\u0027s structure and blood flow. It can confirm the diagnosis of ASD, determine its size and location, and assess the hemodynamic consequences. Doppler echocardiography is particularly useful in paediatric patients as it does not involve radiation exposure and can be performed without sedation in most cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E might show cardiomegaly or increased pulmonary vascularity in ASD, but it lacks the sensitivity and specificity to diagnose the condition definitively. While it can provide useful information about heart size and pulmonary circulation, it cannot directly visualise the atrial septum or quantify the shunt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that can provide detailed hemodynamic information and allow for direct visualisation of the ASD. However, it is not typically used as the initial diagnostic test for suspected ASD in children due to its invasive nature and associated risks. It is usually reserved for cases where echocardiography is inconclusive or when interventional treatment is being considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for a 15-month-old child. Moreover, while it can assess functional capacity, it does not provide direct information about cardiac structure and is not used for diagnosing ASDs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrocardiogram (ECG)\u003C/strong\u003E may show right axis deviation or right bundle branch block in ASD, but these findings are neither sensitive nor specific. While an ECG can provide information about heart rhythm and conduction, it cannot directly visualise cardiac structures or blood flow, making it less useful than echocardiography for diagnosing ASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, Doppler echocardiography is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation for suspected ASD in a child, offering detailed structural and functional information without the risks associated with invasive procedures or radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Doppler echocardiography is the gold standard non-invasive test for diagnosing atrial septal defects in children.","A widely split S2 heart sound, exertional dyspnoea, and a thrill at the left upper sternal border are classic signs of an atrial septal defect.","Atrial septal defects can cause right-sided volume overload, leading to mild hepatomegaly in children."],"references":["Menillo AM, Lee LS, Pearson-Shaver AL. Atrial Septal Defect. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535440/","Anavekar NS, Oh JK. Doppler echocardiography: a contemporary review. J Cardiol. 2009;54(3):347-58. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19944309/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1357"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T22:11:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T22:14:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115676"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"